import pandas as pd
data = pd.read_csv('flood.csv')
df = pd.DataFrame(data)
print(f"Count of over 50% likely: {((df['FloodProbability'] >= 0.50).sum())}")
print(f"Count of less than 50% likely: {((df['FloodProbability'] < 0.50).sum())}")
print(f"All rows of data: {len(df)}")

Count of over 50% likely: 25513
Count of less than 50% likely: 24487
All rows of data: 50000

Options
=======
The options below are convenience aliases to configurable class-options,
as listed in the "Equivalent to" description-line of the aliases.
To see all configurable class-options for some <cmd>, use:
    <cmd> --help-all

--debug
    set log level to logging.DEBUG (maximize logging output)
    Equivalent to: [--Application.log_level=10]
--show-config
    Show the application's configuration (human-readable format)
    Equivalent to: [--Application.show_config=True]
--show-config-json
    Show the application's configuration (json format)
    Equivalent to: [--Application.show_config_json=True]
--generate-config
    generate default config file
    Equivalent to: [--JupyterApp.generate_config=True]
-y
    Answer yes to any questions instead of prompting.
    Equivalent to: [--JupyterApp.answer_yes=True]
--execute
    Execute the notebook prior to export.
    Equivalent to: [--ExecutePreprocessor.enabled=True]
--allow-errors
    Continue notebook execution even if one of the cells throws an error and include the error message in the cell output (the default behaviour is to abort conversion). This flag is only relevant if '--execute' was specified, too.
    Equivalent to: [--ExecutePreprocessor.allow_errors=True]
--stdin
    read a single notebook file from stdin. Write the resulting notebook with default basename 'notebook.*'
    Equivalent to: [--NbConvertApp.from_stdin=True]
--stdout
    Write notebook output to stdout instead of files.
    Equivalent to: [--NbConvertApp.writer_class=StdoutWriter]
--inplace
    Run nbconvert in place, overwriting the existing notebook (only
            relevant when converting to notebook format)
    Equivalent to: [--NbConvertApp.use_output_suffix=False --NbConvertApp.export_format=notebook --FilesWriter.build_directory=]
--clear-output
    Clear output of current file and save in place,
            overwriting the existing notebook.
    Equivalent to: [--NbConvertApp.use_output_suffix=False --NbConvertApp.export_format=notebook --FilesWriter.build_directory= --ClearOutputPreprocessor.enabled=True]
--coalesce-streams
    Coalesce consecutive stdout and stderr outputs into one stream (within each cell).
    Equivalent to: [--NbConvertApp.use_output_suffix=False --NbConvertApp.export_format=notebook --FilesWriter.build_directory= --CoalesceStreamsPreprocessor.enabled=True]
--no-prompt
    Exclude input and output prompts from converted document.
    Equivalent to: [--TemplateExporter.exclude_input_prompt=True --TemplateExporter.exclude_output_prompt=True]
--no-input
    Exclude input cells and output prompts from converted document.
            This mode is ideal for generating code-free reports.
    Equivalent to: [--TemplateExporter.exclude_output_prompt=True --TemplateExporter.exclude_input=True --TemplateExporter.exclude_input_prompt=True]
--allow-chromium-download
    Whether to allow downloading chromium if no suitable version is found on the system.
    Equivalent to: [--WebPDFExporter.allow_chromium_download=True]
--disable-chromium-sandbox
    Disable chromium security sandbox when converting to PDF..
    Equivalent to: [--WebPDFExporter.disable_sandbox=True]
--show-input
    Shows code input. This flag is only useful for dejavu users.
    Equivalent to: [--TemplateExporter.exclude_input=False]
--embed-images
    Embed the images as base64 dataurls in the output. This flag is only useful for the HTML/WebPDF/Slides exports.
    Equivalent to: [--HTMLExporter.embed_images=True]
--sanitize-html
    Whether the HTML in Markdown cells and cell outputs should be sanitized..
    Equivalent to: [--HTMLExporter.sanitize_html=True]
--log-level=<Enum>
    Set the log level by value or name.
    Choices: any of [0, 10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 'DEBUG', 'INFO', 'WARN', 'ERROR', 'CRITICAL']
    Default: 30
    Equivalent to: [--Application.log_level]
--config=<Unicode>
    Full path of a config file.
    Default: ''
    Equivalent to: [--JupyterApp.config_file]
--to=<Unicode>
    The export format to be used, either one of the built-in formats
            ['asciidoc', 'custom', 'html', 'latex', 'markdown', 'notebook', 'pdf', 'python', 'qtpdf', 'qtpng', 'rst', 'script', 'slides', 'webpdf']
            or a dotted object name that represents the import path for an
            ``Exporter`` class
    Default: ''
    Equivalent to: [--NbConvertApp.export_format]
--template=<Unicode>
    Name of the template to use
    Default: ''
    Equivalent to: [--TemplateExporter.template_name]
--template-file=<Unicode>
    Name of the template file to use
    Default: None
    Equivalent to: [--TemplateExporter.template_file]
--theme=<Unicode>
    Template specific theme(e.g. the name of a JupyterLab CSS theme distributed
    as prebuilt extension for the lab template)
    Default: 'light'
    Equivalent to: [--HTMLExporter.theme]
--sanitize_html=<Bool>
    Whether the HTML in Markdown cells and cell outputs should be sanitized.This
    should be set to True by nbviewer or similar tools.
    Default: False
    Equivalent to: [--HTMLExporter.sanitize_html]

    Default: '{notebook_name}'

                                  previous default behaviour (outputting to the current
                                  working directory) use . as the flag value.
    Default: ''
    Equivalent to: [--FilesWriter.build_directory]
--reveal-prefix=<Unicode>
    The URL prefix for reveal.js (version 3.x).
            This defaults to the reveal CDN, but can be any url pointing to a copy
            of reveal.js.
            For speaker notes to work, this must be a relative path to a local
            copy of reveal.js: e.g., "reveal.js".
            If a relative path is given, it must be a subdirectory of the
            current directory (from which the server is run).
            See the usage documentation
            (https://nbconvert.readthedocs.io/en/latest/usage.html#reveal-js-html-slideshow)
            for more details.
    Default: ''

--nbformat=<Enum>
    The nbformat version to write.
            Use this to downgrade notebooks.
    Choices: any of [1, 2, 3, 4]
    Default: 4
    Equivalent to: [--NotebookExporter.nbformat_version]

Examples
--------

    The simplest way to use nbconvert is

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to html

            Options include ['asciidoc', 'custom', 'html', 'latex', 'markdown', 'notebook', 'pdf', 'python', 'qtpdf', 'qtpng', 'rst', 'script', 'slides', 'webpdf'].

            > jupyter nbconvert --to latex mynotebook.ipynb

            Both HTML and LaTeX support multiple output templates. LaTeX includes
            'base', 'article' and 'report'.  HTML includes 'basic', 'lab' and
            'classic'. You can specify the flavor of the format used.

            > jupyter nbconvert --to html --template lab mynotebook.ipynb

            You can also pipe the output to stdout, rather than a file

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --stdout

            PDF is generated via latex

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to pdf

            You can get (and serve) a Reveal.js-powered slideshow

            > jupyter nbconvert myslides.ipynb --to slides --post serve

            Multiple notebooks can be given at the command line in a couple of
            different ways:

            > jupyter nbconvert notebook*.ipynb
            > jupyter nbconvert notebook1.ipynb notebook2.ipynb

            or you can specify the notebooks list in a config file, containing::

                c.NbConvertApp.notebooks = ["my_notebook.ipynb"]

            > jupyter nbconvert --config mycfg.py

To see all available configurables, use `--help-all`.

df["LikelyhoodOfFlood"] = df["FloodProbability"].apply(lambda x: 1 if x >= 0.50 else 0)
print(df.columns)
print(f"Likely count: {(df['LikelyhoodOfFlood'] == 1).sum()}")
print(f"Unlikely count: {(df['LikelyhoodOfFlood'] == 0).sum()}")

In[]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
columns = []
for col in df.columns:
    columns.append(col)
    print(col)
fig, axes = plt.subplots(11, 2, figsize=(40, 35))
axes = axes.flatten()

for i, col in enumerate(columns):
    mean_val = df[col].mean()
    std_dev = df[col].std()

    axes[i].hist(df[col], bins=20, color=np.random.rand(3,), edgecolor='black')
    axes[i].set_title(f'{col} (Mean: {mean_val:.2f}, Std Dev: {std_dev:.2f})', fontsize=10)
    axes[i].set_xlabel(col, fontsize=8)
    axes[i].set_ylabel('Count', fontsize=8)
    axes[i].axvline(mean_val, color='red', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=2)
    axes[i].axvline(mean_val + std_dev, color='green', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=2)
    axes[i].axvline(mean_val - std_dev, color='green', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=2)


plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.6)
plt.savefig("InitialHistograms.png")
plt.show()

In[]:
dfNorm = df.copy()
for column in df.columns:
    col_min = df[column].min()
    col_max = df[column].max()
    dfNorm[column] = (df[column] - col_min) / (col_max - col_min)

statistics = dfNorm[columns].describe().transpose()
print(tabulate(statistics, headers='keys', tablefmt='grid', showindex=True))

columns = []
for col in dfNorm.columns:
    columns.append(col)
    print(col)
fig, axes = plt.subplots(11, 2, figsize=(40, 35))
axes = axes.flatten()

for i, col in enumerate(columns):
    mean_val = dfNorm[col].mean()
    std_dev = dfNorm[col].std()

    axes[i].hist(dfNorm[col], bins=20, color=np.random.rand(3,), edgecolor='black')
    axes[i].set_title(f'Normalized {col} (Mean: {mean_val:.2f}, Std Dev: {std_dev:.2f})', fontsize=10)
    axes[i].set_xlabel(col, fontsize=8)
    axes[i].set_ylabel('Count', fontsize=8)
    axes[i].axvline(mean_val, color='red', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=2)
    axes[i].axvline(mean_val + std_dev, color='green', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=2)
    axes[i].axvline(mean_val - std_dev, color='green', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=2)


plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.6)
plt.savefig("InitialHistograms.png")
plt.show()

from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense
model = Sequential()
model.add(Dense(1,input_dim = len(df.columns)-1,activation = "sigmoid"))
model.compile(loss="binary_crossentropy",optimizer = "rmsprop", metrics = ["accuracy"])

import random

print(dfNorm)
dataset = dfNorm.to_numpy()
np.random.shuffle(dataset)
index_30percent = int(0.3 * len(dataset[:, 0]))
print(index_30percent)
XVALID = dataset[:index_30percent, :-2]
YVALID = dataset[:index_30percent, -1]
XTRAIN = dataset[index_30percent:, :-2]
YTRAIN = dataset[index_30percent:, -1]

def normalizize(TRAIN, valid):
  means = TRAIN.mean(axis=0)
  std = TRAIN.std(axis=0)
  trainNorm = (TRAIN - means) / std
  validNorm = (valid - means) / std
  return trainNorm, validNorm

XTRAIN,XVALID = normalizize(XTRAIN,XVALID)

print(YTRAIN[:10])

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.metrics import precision_score, recall_score, f1_score
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense
from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import ModelCheckpoint, EarlyStopping

#Logisitic Model
model = Sequential()
model.add(Dense(8, input_dim=len(XTRAIN[0, :]), activation='sigmoid'))
model.add(Dense(4, activation='sigmoid'))
model.add(Dense(2, activation='sigmoid'))
model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))


model.compile(loss="binary_crossentropy", optimizer="rmsprop", metrics=["accuracy"])
checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint(f"logistic.h5.keras", monitor="val_accuracy", save_best_only=True, mode="max", verbose=1)
early_stopping = EarlyStopping(monitor="val_loss", patience=5, restore_best_weights=True, mode="min", verbose=1)


history = model.fit(XTRAIN, YTRAIN, epochs=10, batch_size=32, validation_data=(XVALID, YVALID), callbacks=[checkpoint, early_stopping])


valLoss, valAcc = model.evaluate(XVALID, YVALID)
trainLoss, trainAcc = model.evaluate(XTRAIN, YTRAIN)

resultLogistic =  {"neurons": "16,4,2,1",
                   "layers": 4,
                   "val_loss": valLoss,
                   "val_accuracy": valAcc,
                   "train_loss": trainLoss,
                   "train_accuracy": trainAcc,
                   "history": history.history}


predictions = model.predict(XVALID)
predictions = (predictions > 0.5).astype(int)


precision = precision_score(YVALID, predictions)
recall = recall_score(YVALID, predictions)
f1 = f1_score(YVALID, predictions)


print(f"Precision: {precision}")
print(f"Recall: {recall}")
print(f"F1 Score: {f1}")


plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))


plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.plot(history.history['accuracy'], label='Train Accuracy')
plt.plot(history.history['val_accuracy'], label='Validation Accuracy')
plt.title('Learning Curves Logisitic - Accuracy')
plt.xlabel('Epochs')
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.legend()


plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
plt.plot(history.history['loss'], label='Train Loss')
plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'], label='Validation Loss')
plt.title('Learning Curves Logistic - Loss')
plt.xlabel('Epochs')
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.legend()
plt.savefig("Logistic.png")

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()


def createAModel(neurons, layers):
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(neurons[0], input_dim=len(XTRAIN[0, :]), activation='relu'))
    for i in range(1, layers):
        model.add(Dense(neurons[i], activation='relu'))

    model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))

    model.summary()

    model.compile(loss="binary_crossentropy", optimizer="adam", metrics=["accuracy"])
    return model

model1 = createAModel([64,32,16,8],3)
model2 = createAModel([32,16,8,1],3)
model3 = createAModel([16,8,1],3)
model4 = createAModel([8,1],1)
model5 = createAModel([4,1],1)
model6 = createAModel([2,1],1)

# TrainEval function now calls the new evaluation code
def trainEval(model, neurons, layers):
    results = []

    checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint(f"best_model_{neurons}_{layers}.h5.keras",
                                 monitor="val_accuracy",
                                 save_best_only=True,
                                 mode="max",
                                 verbose=1)

    early_stopping = EarlyStopping(monitor="val_loss",
                                   patience=5,
                                   restore_best_weights=True,
                                   mode="min",
                                   verbose=1)

    history = model.fit(XTRAIN, YTRAIN, epochs=10, batch_size=32,
                        validation_data=(XVALID, YVALID),
                        callbacks=[checkpoint, early_stopping])

    valLoss, valAcc = model.evaluate(XVALID, YVALID)
    trainLoss, trainAcc = model.evaluate(XTRAIN, YTRAIN)

    predictions = model.predict(XVALID)
    predictions = (predictions > 0.5).astype(int)

    precision = precision_score(YVALID, predictions)
    recall = recall_score(YVALID, predictions)
    f1 = f1_score(YVALID, predictions)

    results.append({
        "neurons": neurons,
        "layers": layers,
        "val_loss": valLoss,
        "val_accuracy": valAcc,
        "train_loss": trainLoss,
        "train_accuracy": trainAcc,
        "precision": precision,
        "recall": recall,
        "f1": f1,
        "history": history.history
    })

    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plt.plot(history.history['accuracy'], label='Train Accuracy')
    plt.plot(history.history['val_accuracy'], label='Validation Accuracy')
    plt.title(f'Learning Curves {neurons,layers} - Accuracy')
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.legend()


    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plt.plot(history.history['loss'], label='Train Loss')
    plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'], label='Validation Loss')
    plt.title(f'Learning Curves {neurons, layers}- Loss')
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.legend()
    plt.savefig(f"{neurons,layers}.png")

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

    return results

results1 = trainEval(model1, [64, 32, 16, 8], 4)
results2 = trainEval(model2, [32, 16, 8, 1], 4)
results3 = trainEval(model3, [16, 8, 1], 3)
results4 = trainEval(model4, [8, 1], 2)
results5 = trainEval(model5, [4, 1], 2)
results6 = trainEval(model6, [2, 1], 2)

            "val_accuracy": res["val_accuracy"],
            "train_loss": res["train_loss"],
            "train_accuracy": res["train_accuracy"],
            "precision": res["precision"],
            "recall": res["recall"],
            "f1": res["f1"]
        })

dfR = pd.DataFrame(allResults)

baseline_predictions = np.full_like(YVALID, majority_class)
baseline_accuracy = np.mean(baseline_predictions == YVALID)

In[]:
def trainModelWithOneFeature():
    results = []
    for i in range(XTRAIN.shape[1]):
        XTRAINcol = XTRAIN[:, i].reshape(-1, 1)
        XVALIDcol = XVALID[:, i].reshape(-1, 1)
        model = Sequential()
        model.add(Dense(8, input_dim=1, activation='relu'))
        model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))

        model.compile(loss="binary_crossentropy", optimizer="adam", metrics=["accuracy"])

        checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint(f"best_model_featureIndex{i}.h5.keras",
                                      monitor="val_accuracy",
                                      save_best_only=True,
                                      mode="max",
                                      verbose=1)

        early_stopping = EarlyStopping(monitor="val_loss",
                                       patience=5,
                                       restore_best_weights=True,
                                       mode="min",
                                       verbose=1)

        history = model.fit(XTRAINcol, YTRAIN, epochs=10, batch_size=32,
                            validation_data=(XVALIDcol, YVALID),
                            callbacks=[checkpoint, early_stopping])

        valLoss, valAcc = model.evaluate(XVALIDcol, YVALID)
        trainLoss, trainAcc = model.evaluate(XTRAINcol, YTRAIN)

        predictions = model.predict(XVALIDcol)
        predictions = (predictions > 0.5).astype(int)

        precision = precision_score(YVALID, predictions)
        recall = recall_score(YVALID, predictions)
        f1 = f1_score(YVALID, predictions)

        results.append({
            "FeatureIndex": i,
            "ValidationAccuracy": valAcc,
            "TrainingAccuracy": trainAcc,
            "ValidationLoss": valLoss,
            "TrainingLoss": trainLoss,
            "Precision": precision,
            "Recall": recall,
            "F1Score": f1
        })

    feature_indices = [f"Feature {result['FeatureIndex']+1}" for result in results]
    validation_accuracies = [result["ValidationAccuracy"] for result in results]
    y_min, y_max = (0.8, 1.0) if all(acc > 0.8 for acc in validation_accuracies) else (0.0, 1.0)

    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    plt.bar(feature_indices, validation_accuracies, color='skyblue')
    plt.ylim(y_min, y_max)
    plt.title("Validation Accuracies for Individual Features")
    plt.xlabel("Features")
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)
    plt.ylabel("Validation Accuracy")
    plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.69)
    plt.savefig("indv_columns.png")
    plt.show()

    return results

allResultsCol = trainModelWithOneFeature()

In[]:
def trainModelWithReducedFeatures(allResultsCol):
    # Sort features by validation accuracy (ascending order, least important first)
    sorted_results = sorted(allResultsCol, key=lambda x: x["ValidationAccuracy"])
    feature_importance_order = [res["FeatureIndex"] for res in sorted_results]

    validation_accuracies = []
    training_accuracies = []
    num_features = len(feature_importance_order)

    for i in range(num_features):

        remaining_features = feature_importance_order[i:]
        XTRAIN_reduced = XTRAIN[:, remaining_features]
        XVALID_reduced = XVALID[:, remaining_features]


        model = Sequential()
        model.add(Dense(8, input_dim=XTRAIN_reduced.shape[1], activation='relu'))
        model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))

        model.compile(loss="binary_crossentropy", optimizer="adam", metrics=["accuracy"])


        early_stopping = EarlyStopping(
            monitor="val_loss", patience=5, restore_best_weights=True, mode="min", verbose=1
        )


        model_checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint(
            filepath=f"removed_{i}_features.keras",
            monitor="val_loss",
            save_best_only=True,
            verbose=1,
            mode="min",
        )

        # Train the model
        history = model.fit(
            XTRAIN_reduced,
            YTRAIN,
            epochs=50,
            batch_size=32,
            validation_data=(XVALID_reduced, YVALID),
            callbacks=[early_stopping, model_checkpoint],
        )


        valLoss, valAcc = model.evaluate(XVALID_reduced, YVALID, verbose=0)
        trainLoss, trainAcc = model.evaluate(XTRAIN_reduced, YTRAIN, verbose=0)


        validation_accuracies.append(valAcc)
        training_accuracies.append(trainAcc)


    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    plt.plot(
        range(num_features, 0, -1),
        validation_accuracies,
        marker="o",
        label="Validation Accuracy",
        color="skyblue",
    )
    plt.plot(
        range(num_features, 0, -1),
        training_accuracies,
        marker="o",
        label="Training Accuracy",
        color="orange",
    )
    plt.title("Validation Accuracy vs. Number of Features")
    plt.xlabel("Number of Features Remaining")
    plt.ylabel("Accuracy")
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(axis="y", linestyle="--", alpha=0.69)
    plt.savefig("validation_accuracy_reduced_features.png")
    plt.show()

    return validation_accuracies, training_accuracies

validation_accuracies, training_accuracies = trainModelWithReducedFeatures(allResultsCol)

num_features = len(validation_accuracies)


plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

plt.plot(
    range(1, num_features + 1),
    validation_accuracies,
    marker="o",
    label="Validation Accuracy",
    color="skyblue",
)


plt.plot(
    range(1, num_features + 1),
    training_accuracies,
    marker="o",
    label="Training Accuracy",
    color="orange",
)

# Title and labels
plt.title("Validation Accuracy vs. Number of Features")
plt.xlabel("Number of Features Removed (Sorted by unimportance)")
plt.ylabel("Accuracy")


plt.xticks(range(1, num_features + 1))


plt.legend()
plt.grid(axis="y", linestyle="--", alpha=0.69)


plt.savefig("validation_accuracy_reduced_features.png")
plt.show()
